90
00:06:38,129 --> 00:06:42,232
It's like when you push the input, you want that to feel good and you want it to feel

91
00:06:42,252 --> 00:06:43,273
like you're Sam Fisher.

92
00:06:43,293 --> 00:06:44,794
That's going to really embody the pamper.

93
00:06:45,594 --> 00:06:45,875
Okay?

94
00:06:46,175 --> 00:06:49,697
And with realism, it was about Sam and the enemies having an awareness of the world around

95
00:06:49,717 --> 00:06:50,138
them, as I said.

96
00:06:52,015 --> 00:06:57,661
I wanted everything to feel very tactile. I think I'd just seen Children of Man and there was lots of like touching the walls and all this sort of stuff.

97
00:06:58,082 --> 00:07:00,764
And I was obsessed with like grounding the character to that.

98
00:07:01,826 --> 00:07:06,470
You know, it's like I wanted the AI to communicate visually. I didn't just want them to have audio barks.

99
00:07:07,531 --> 00:07:13,298
I wanted them to actually be signalling to each other. Whether the player was going to see that, I didn't really care. It was more of I just wanted them to be communicating.

100
00:07:14,880 --> 00:07:19,601
And with all that awareness, it wouldn't be much fun if everything wasn't reactive.

101
00:07:20,161 --> 00:07:24,202
So Sam and the AI would need to be visually reacting different to each other.

102
00:07:24,502 --> 00:07:28,003
You know, I wanted people to react to explosions, I wanted to be able to fire a gun in the air,

103
00:07:28,043 --> 00:07:29,724
