00:14:41,555 --> 00:14:45,837
ladder climbing, ledge jumping and some of these things. Some made it in the game, some didn't.

249
00:14:48,202 --> 00:14:52,823
Also, we wanted to really focus on how crouch navigation was working as well, because we

250
00:14:52,864 --> 00:14:54,664
knew that players were going to be using that a lot.

251
00:14:56,404 --> 00:14:59,125
And finally, there was a bunch of new AI archetypes that we were going to add.

252
00:14:59,485 --> 00:15:03,126
So all of this was going to need animation support, and this was all on top of things

253
00:15:03,146 --> 00:15:03,806
that were already there.

254
00:15:05,807 --> 00:15:10,348
Okay, so just to give you a quick idea, Conviction's animation budget was about 40 meg.

255
00:15:11,409 --> 00:15:13,551
So I don't know how much that means to anyone,

256
00:15:13,831 --> 00:15:15,272
but that's a decent amount.

257
00:15:15,292 --> 00:15:16,774
You can normally get quite a lot done with that.

258
00:15:16,854 --> 00:15:17,614
So I was like, great.

259
00:15:17,895 --> 00:15:20,036
Considering the scope, if we get that for Blacklist,

260
00:15:21,417 --> 00:15:21,978
then we'll be fine.

261
00:15:22,098 --> 00:15:22,839
But we got 23.

262
00:15:24,520 --> 00:15:25,721
So how are we going to do that?

263
00:15:27,843 --> 00:15:32,887
OK, so what I wanted to do is I knew that we needed mocap.

264
00:15:34,130 --> 00:15:36,752
just due to the sheer amount of animation we're going to need.

265
00:15:36,932 --> 00:15:39,714
We knew that we were going to invest in a solid MoCAP pipeline.

266
00:15:40,534 --> 00:15:43,436
MoCAP would allow us to keep as much of the integrity of Kevin's moves

267
00:15:43,476 --> 00:15:43,916
as possible.

268
00:15:45,217 --> 00:15:46,718
And when it wouldn't be possible to MoCAP,

269
00:15:46,778 --> 00:15:48,899
we'd need strong animators to help prototype systems.

270
00:15:49,559 --> 00:15:54,182
Because MoCAP wasn't always going to be the solution.

271
00:15:54,302 --> 00:15:56,563
Sometimes they need to animate some of the more difficult systems,

272
00:15:56,603 --> 00:15:58,664
some of the things that we didn't want to go to MoCAP with that we

273
00:15:58,704 --> 00:15:59,985
might end up getting sued over.

274
00:16:01,606 --> 00:16:01,846
Also.

275
00:16:02,888 --> 00:16:04,549
I knew we'd need to improve the animation tools.

276
00:16:05,389 --> 00:16:09,890
The tools were already existing and were functional for all the previous games.

277
00:16:10,830 --> 00:16:13,751
But we knew that to reach the level of quality and to do everything on time

278
00:16:14,391 --> 00:16:17,732
and just to get everything in, we knew we were going to have to work on

279
00:16:17,772 --> 00:16:21,633
increased animator control so animators could play around with things and really try and experiment.

280
00:16:22,013 --> 00:16:25,314
And we also knew we were going to have to somehow find massive memory savings.

281
00:16:26,550 --> 00:16:29,255
uh... okay and of course the scope didn't just apply to the animation team

282
00:16:29,275 --> 00:16:30,577
is every team had this mandate

283
00:16:30,978 --> 00:16:33,142
so every team we're gonna have to add more so

284
00:16:33,983 --> 00:16:35,386
they all have to go through the same sort of problems

285
00:16:37,286 --> 00:16:44,548
Okay, at Ubisoft we were really lucky that headquarters saw to invest in us as like a

286
00:16:44,648 --> 00:16:46,808
center for performance capture.

287
00:16:47,028 --> 00:16:51,189
We actually asked for like a smaller system, but then Montreal was getting so booked up

288
00:16:51,309 --> 00:16:54,490
with all their mocap shoots that they said, well, we'll just build you a studio.

289
00:16:54,870 --> 00:16:58,151
I mean, that's great, but we didn't want to waste it.

290
00:16:59,511 --> 00:17:03,434
I mean, gameplay shoots for me have different objectives from cinematics.

291
00:17:05,075 --> 00:17:08,597
The focus shifts between the aesthetic, how it might feel to play, and the technical constraints

292
00:17:08,617 --> 00:17:09,177
that are involved.

293
00:17:10,118 --> 00:17:12,719
Our moves need to look good from all angles at all times.

294
00:17:13,800 --> 00:17:17,602
So what I like to do is I like to focus, I don't like to have too many people on set.

295
00:17:19,203 --> 00:17:22,745
But basically, for me to run a gameplay shoot, I like to keep things nice and simple.

296
00:17:22,785 --> 00:17:26,628
So over the past 14 years, there's been some simple guidelines that I like to follow.

297
00:17:28,701 --> 00:17:32,704
Okay, as I said, I like to limit the number of people on set at one time.

298
00:17:33,604 --> 00:17:36,806
I find that if a set is too busy, you get distracted.

299
00:17:37,167 --> 00:17:39,368
Keeping the numbers down helps keep everyone focused.

300
00:17:39,869 --> 00:17:40,909
Everyone knows their role.

301
00:17:41,350 --> 00:17:42,750
Usually, that would mean myself directing.

302
00:17:42,851 --> 00:17:46,433
We'd have our team lead basically keeping hold of the Excel sheet

303
00:17:46,453 --> 00:17:47,534
and making sure that we got all the shots.

304
00:17:47,614 --> 00:17:50,396
And she would always offer a really valuable second opinion.

305
00:17:51,437 --> 00:17:56,644
Of course, you've got the actors, usually two, and we'd usually invite one or two animators

306
00:17:56,684 --> 00:18:00,009
onto the stage as well, just if they were going to be working with those moves, just

307
00:18:00,029 --> 00:18:03,113
so they could understand where the intention and everything was coming from.

308
00:18:03,313 --> 00:18:06,378
Because if we just gave them the moves, then they might lose some of the aesthetic.

309
00:18:08,649 --> 00:18:12,051
It seems obvious, but everyone on set needs to know who's directing.

310
00:18:13,372 --> 00:18:15,474
And you know, I like to be the alpha.

311
00:18:15,935 --> 00:18:17,476
So it's like, I'll be on set.

312
00:18:17,656 --> 00:18:18,757
The actors need to know as well.

313
00:18:19,157 --> 00:18:20,258
It helps keep the vision clear.

314
00:18:21,699 --> 00:18:25,042
They know that they can go to you if they have any issues.

315
00:18:25,162 --> 00:18:28,545
And you know, you don't really want people kind of chiming in with opinions all the time

316
00:18:28,585 --> 00:18:30,126
because again, things get really confusing.

317
00:18:30,206 --> 00:18:32,348
So it's always good to kind of filter things through one person.

318
00:18:35,314 --> 00:18:38,788
Something I found that worked really, really well with Kevin was collaboration.

319
00:18:40,358 --> 00:18:43,581
To me that's the key to success with working with mocap, especially for gameplay shoots,

320
00:18:44,161 --> 00:18:48,245
is I like to work with goals in mind, not necessarily a direction.

321
00:18:49,346 --> 00:18:53,010
Sometimes I'll have a very, very clear idea of what I want and then work with that, but

322
00:18:53,090 --> 00:18:59,436
more often than not, if I have a goal like, okay, you start here, you end there, do something

323
00:18:59,456 --> 00:19:04,321
in the middle, and make it look badass, then Kevin more often than not came up with something

324
00:19:04,341 --> 00:19:04,701
that worked.

325
00:19:06,964 --> 00:19:10,587
Okay, with that said, you need to be respectful of your talent.

326
00:19:10,848 --> 00:19:19,836
I mean, there's no point in having your actors working on crouch moves all morning where

327
00:19:19,856 --> 00:19:22,418
it's going to kill their legs and then you go, oh yeah, by the way, in the afternoon

328
00:19:22,438 --> 00:19:23,439
we're going to have you beat someone up.

329
00:19:23,919 --> 00:19:25,100
Then that's not going to work.

330
00:19:25,200 --> 00:19:28,263
It's going to, unless you want them to look tired when they do it, then it's not going

331
00:19:28,283 --> 00:19:28,463
to work.

332
00:19:30,741 --> 00:19:32,903
to me if a particular move is giving you trouble

333
00:19:33,603 --> 00:19:34,203
uh... move it around

334
00:19:34,704 --> 00:19:35,704
you know move on to the next one

335
00:19:36,585 --> 00:19:39,927
uh... it's it's it's going to get your actors frustrated it's going to get the people on

336
00:19:39,967 --> 00:19:40,748
set frustrated

337
00:19:41,088 --> 00:19:43,790
is that you can always come back to it later and that you never know it's like

338
00:19:43,810 --> 00:19:45,712
you know it's like it's like almost like you're sleeping on it

339
00:19:45,952 --> 00:19:47,213
you'll have a better idea of what you want to do

340
00:19:48,274 --> 00:19:49,794
And personally, I like to go to MoCap

341
00:19:49,834 --> 00:19:53,095
with an almost impossible list of moves that I'm looking for.

342
00:19:53,215 --> 00:19:55,735
So if I manage to capture everything I need,

343
00:19:56,435 --> 00:19:58,496
I let the actors kind of play with some of the things

344
00:19:58,616 --> 00:20:00,676
I need to do in the afternoon.

345
00:20:00,916 --> 00:20:04,437
And we actually got some really cool stuff from that as well,

346
00:20:04,637 --> 00:20:06,937
and some ideas that may end up just ending in the game

347
00:20:07,097 --> 00:20:08,037
that you didn't actually think of.

348
00:20:10,078 --> 00:20:12,638
OK, so this stage became our playground,

349
00:20:13,959 --> 00:20:16,639
with Kevin becoming kind of the one constant on set.

350
00:20:17,597 --> 00:20:22,482
But we found to get the most out of Kevin, we had to employ a stunt guy that would work.

351
00:20:22,802 --> 00:20:26,046
Originally we had Kevin come in with one of his guys from the dojo, but the problem is

352
00:20:26,726 --> 00:20:31,070
he knew Kevin so well that he was anticipating everything and wouldn't show any pain, so

353
00:20:31,090 --> 00:20:33,052
he just, the data looked terrible.

354
00:20:33,152 --> 00:20:35,415
So we got a guy in that had no idea who Kevin was.

355
00:20:37,657 --> 00:20:39,198
That was a very interesting first meeting.

356
00:20:40,259 --> 00:20:42,281
Especially considering Kevin's never been on set before.

357
00:20:43,022 --> 00:20:44,364
He doesn't know what half speed is.

358
00:20:44,864 --> 00:20:46,846
Kevin just goes, boom, that's it.

359
00:20:47,427 --> 00:20:51,211
So if these guys didn't know how to take a hit, then we could have been in trouble.

360
00:20:51,711 --> 00:20:55,695
So I want to show you a quick kind of compilation of one of the shoots that we did.

361
00:21:50,078 --> 00:21:51,099
So that's Kevin Sikor.

362
00:21:53,984 --> 00:21:56,487
I had to deal with that guy every day for three years.

363
00:21:58,270 --> 00:22:02,316
Anyway, so the cool thing is we're

364
00:22:02,336 --> 00:22:03,538
starting to get into the meat of things now.

365
00:22:05,215 --> 00:22:07,698
We get this data, what do we do with it?

366
00:22:08,799 --> 00:22:11,903
Now the thing is with Kevin, again with it being the first time him being on set

367
00:22:13,044 --> 00:22:15,066
he didn't really know how to sell an action

368
00:22:15,687 --> 00:22:17,369
he didn't really know what it was going to look like in game

369
00:22:18,370 --> 00:22:21,474
so as you can see on the left, it's the raw mocap, it looks pretty cool

370
00:22:21,674 --> 00:22:23,977
you can see what's going on, I think it's like a kidney attack or something

371
00:22:24,759 --> 00:22:26,422
But on the right is what we did to it.

372
00:22:27,944 --> 00:22:30,488
And you can see that we've kind of accentuated

373
00:22:30,508 --> 00:22:31,229
some of the lines.

374
00:22:31,549 --> 00:22:33,032
We've made things a little bit more aggressive.

375
00:22:33,072 --> 00:22:34,073
We've cleaned up the feet.

376
00:22:34,574 --> 00:22:36,116
We've made things look a little bit,

377
00:22:36,136 --> 00:22:37,378
they've got a lot more impact.

378
00:22:37,618 --> 00:22:39,721
I mean, we keep everything on the move as well.

379
00:22:40,983 --> 00:22:44,544
And this was kind of typical to what we do to some of the animations.

380
00:22:44,884 --> 00:22:51,647
The thing is, is this particular move is Kevin did it at such a speed that we hardly have to do anything to it except to just accentuate it.

381
00:22:52,187 --> 00:22:53,367
So the timing was there.

382
00:22:54,107 --> 00:22:55,148
So again, it's kind of crazy.

383
00:22:57,769 --> 00:23:02,790
So I'm going to give you kind of a breakdown on one of the particular moves that we decided to add for Blacklist.

384
00:23:03,110 --> 00:23:04,031
We called them abductions.

385
00:23:04,311 --> 00:23:09,913
They were seen as cover takedowns, and they fitted really, really well with the stealth roots of Splinter Cell.

386
00:23:13,578 --> 00:23:15,880
So some of the choices we made for abductions

387
00:23:17,321 --> 00:23:20,142
were we wanted to be able to pull people into cover

388
00:23:20,162 --> 00:23:22,084
or dispatch them really quickly, hide when

389
00:23:22,104 --> 00:23:23,945
they were in cover as well.

390
00:23:24,045 --> 00:23:27,787
So here is the raw data from one of the moves.

391
00:23:33,198 --> 00:23:35,859
And it's pretty cool, but the thing is, is we can't put that in game.

392
00:23:35,939 --> 00:23:38,400
I mean, what we could, we, what we do is we actually, we do put that in game,

393
00:23:38,680 --> 00:23:42,501
but then we feel how slow it is and how it slows down the gameplay and it doesn't really work.

394
00:23:43,182 --> 00:23:45,102
Um, to me it lacks a bit of impact as well.

395
00:23:45,142 --> 00:23:47,223
I mean, Kevin was good, but he couldn't get

396
00:23:47,243 --> 00:23:49,444
that, the sort of impact that we needed,

397
00:23:49,464 --> 00:23:52,845
because otherwise he would have just, we would have gone through stunt guys like Candy.

398
00:23:53,846 --> 00:23:56,947
Um, see to me there's some broken contacts in there as well.

399
00:23:57,007 --> 00:23:58,548
The hands don't connect properly.

400
00:23:58,888 --> 00:23:59,828
Messy foot positions.

401
00:23:59,868 --> 00:24:02,049
It's a little bit too slow, and I knew I wanted to amp it up.

402
00:24:03,792 --> 00:24:09,619
So then we give it to an animator, and then we usually, after about a week, they come

403
00:24:09,659 --> 00:24:10,520
back with this.

404
00:24:11,161 --> 00:24:16,448
Again, there's some more aggression on there, it's like really smashing the head down, you

405
00:24:16,468 --> 00:24:19,491
know, pulling him into cover with a lot more aggression, dropping the weapon.

406
00:24:20,853 --> 00:24:22,054
So this was starting to work.

407
00:24:23,117 --> 00:24:27,081
So what we'd also do is we'd fix shoulder and neck positions because we find that usually

408
00:24:27,101 --> 00:24:31,564
from mocap is the shoulders would always be really high or the necks would be forward.

409
00:24:32,025 --> 00:24:36,488
And also we wanted the move to kind of fit within five seconds at the maximum and even

410
00:24:36,528 --> 00:24:37,149
that was pushing it.

411
00:24:39,148 --> 00:24:41,830
So once we did that, we'd add one extra layer.

412
00:24:42,390 --> 00:24:44,631
And one of the things I really wanted to do

413
00:24:44,691 --> 00:24:48,172
is I wanted Sam to be aware of everyone all the time.

414
00:24:48,292 --> 00:24:51,133
So now all the animators had gone through and animated

415
00:24:51,153 --> 00:24:52,554
this really cool animation.

416
00:24:52,614 --> 00:24:53,754
I decided I didn't want to show it.

417
00:24:54,595 --> 00:24:59,057
So we animated the cameras to focus on other things.

418
00:24:59,637 --> 00:25:01,738
So you could have all this animation in the background,

419
00:25:02,018 --> 00:25:03,478
but then the camera would be looking somewhere else.

420
00:25:05,673 --> 00:25:10,054
So that also connected to our surgical strike response and awareness.

421
00:25:11,034 --> 00:25:13,195
So again, I'm connecting everything back round, this is really cool.

422
00:25:21,397 --> 00:25:24,157
So as you can see, it's like, well if you can see because it's quite dark,

423
00:25:24,717 --> 00:25:27,358
you've got a guy passing in the background, you've got all the animation happening.

424
00:25:27,918 --> 00:25:28,938
The thing is, is the camera...

425
00:25:29,250 --> 00:25:33,714
control could be interrupted at any point. So that was where the animator work would

426
00:25:33,734 --> 00:25:39,819
be seen. This kind of idea stuck with something we called One Step Ahead. So we wanted Sam

427
00:25:39,839 --> 00:25:44,303
to always be looking at his next target. Once he had something in his hands, then that was

428
00:25:44,363 --> 00:25:48,787
it, he was over. And this was actually something that came from Kevin. Kevin never really looked

429
00:25:48,827 --> 00:25:50,748
at what he was doing, he was always looking at the next thing.

430
00:25:53,148 --> 00:25:56,711
So this would take the animator about a week and I think that by the time towards the end of the project

431
00:25:56,971 --> 00:25:59,253
they managed to be able to do one of these in about a day.

432
00:26:01,394 --> 00:26:04,657
Okay, so one of the other things that we did is we add this thing that we called

433
00:26:04,677 --> 00:26:05,698
the variety node.

434
00:26:07,112 --> 00:26:09,554
And it would basically allow us to create non-standardized loops.

435
00:26:10,514 --> 00:26:12,375
It was like one big long sequence of animation

436
00:26:12,756 --> 00:26:14,077
that we could use as a base

437
00:26:14,697 --> 00:26:16,698
and it meant that Sam could

438
00:26:17,199 --> 00:26:19,840
be here, this was in one of the levels in London

439
00:26:20,281 --> 00:26:21,281
where he was poisoned.

440
00:26:21,602 --> 00:26:23,023
So, spoilers if you haven't played the game.

441
00:26:24,484 --> 00:26:27,245
And we wanted him to stagger around, I had all these ideas for him kind of

442
00:26:27,285 --> 00:26:29,207
leaning against walls and vomiting and

443
00:26:29,727 --> 00:26:31,728
you know, I really wanted him to throw up

444
00:26:32,029 --> 00:26:32,489
for some reason.

445
00:26:34,147 --> 00:26:36,488
So yeah, so this was only possible with a variety.

446
00:26:36,708 --> 00:26:38,749
But the cool thing about this is that

447
00:26:38,769 --> 00:26:40,830
would be used over an existing set of animation.

448
00:26:41,930 --> 00:26:44,111
So we could just have our base movement set

449
00:26:44,131 --> 00:26:46,032
and just replace like six or seven animations.

450
00:26:47,412 --> 00:26:50,053
And all we'd have to do is mark them up as A, B, C, D, et

451
00:26:50,094 --> 00:26:50,694
cetera, et cetera.

452
00:26:50,854 --> 00:26:53,455
And then the engine would see them and then play them

453
00:26:53,475 --> 00:26:53,915
in sequence.

454
00:26:54,375 --> 00:26:55,936
It also meant that if we were clever,

455
00:26:55,976 --> 00:26:57,236
we could play around with that sequence

456
00:26:57,256 --> 00:27:00,918
and create like any number of random-ish sequences.

457
00:27:04,499 --> 00:27:07,684
Okay, replacements was also another thing for us as well.

458
00:27:07,964 --> 00:27:09,767
This scene from the very, very beginning of the game

459
00:27:10,769 --> 00:27:13,212
was actually just replacing a couple of animations

460
00:27:13,413 --> 00:27:18,039
from Sam's base walk set with no weapon in his hand.

461
00:27:19,091 --> 00:27:23,155
uh... and it meant that all we had to do was again create a few animations and

462
00:27:23,195 --> 00:27:24,036
we got the rest for free

463
00:27:24,917 --> 00:27:25,097
uh...

464
00:27:25,117 --> 00:27:28,641
uh... the design team really wanted to show sam kind of gradually

465
00:27:29,121 --> 00:27:29,882
getting better

466
00:27:30,183 --> 00:27:30,803
as he was walking

467
00:27:31,083 --> 00:27:33,886
you know so we wanted to show him really injured at the beginning and originally this was

